ght: 250px;"></div></div></div><div class=3D"contentPart css-12zi0x1"><h2 i=
d=3D"what-are-independent-events">What are independent events?</h2>
<div class=3D"textBlock"><p>In probability, <strong>independent events</str=
ong> are entirely disjointed events: the probability of one occurring (or n=
ot) does not influence the others. Imagine two people in different cities t=
hrowing a coin: the outcome of each toss is <strong>entirely independent</s=
trong> of the other. On the other hand, the first full moon of spring and t=
he date of Easter are dependent events as you can learn from the <a href=3D=
"https://www.calctool.org/other/easter" class=3D"js-link">Easter date calcu=
lation formula</a> - we can predict one based on the other.</p>
<p>Independent events have an important role in statistics and probability =
since dealing with them is way easier than dealing with events that have so=
me degree of <strong>correlation</strong>.</p>
</div></div><div class=3D"contentPart css-12zi0x1"><h2 id=3D"how-to-calcula=
te-the-probability-of-multiple-events">How to calculate the probability of =
